{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563564"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16816"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16816"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.22,0.3,0.21,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9507"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52534"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4154"},{"type":"tags","id":"11990"},{"type":"tags","id":"12231"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic for insertion of a progesterone intrauterine device for heavy menstrual bleeding. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. During the procedure, immediately after applying cervical traction with a tenaculum, she becomes unresponsive. On examination, she appears pale and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 40/min, blood pressure 50/30 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical dilation","Adrenaline","Place the legs down from lithotomy","Normal saline bolus","Atropine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cervical shock, a severe vasovagal response triggered by cervical manipulation during intrauterine device insertion. The profound bradycardia and hypotension are characteristic features of an intense vagal response, which can lead to reduced cerebral perfusion and loss of consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtropine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for severe cervical shock. Atropine, an anticholinergic medication, blocks vagal stimulation and rapidly reverses both the bradycardia and hypotension. The typical dose is 0.5-1.0 mg intravenously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical dilation\u003C/strong\u003E would cause further cervical manipulation and potentially worsen the vagal response. The procedure should be abandoned at this point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for anaphylaxis but is not indicated for vasovagal syncope. The underlying mechanism here is excessive vagal stimulation, which is best addressed with an anticholinergic agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal saline bolus\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful as a supportive measure but will not address the underlying vagal stimulation causing the bradycardia and hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlace the legs down from lithotomy\u003C/strong\u003E position would worsen venous return and potentially exacerbate hypotension. Trendelenburg positioning (head down, legs elevated) would be more appropriate to improve cerebral perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administering atropine, the procedure should be abandoned, and the patient monitored until fully recovered. Future attempts at intrauterine device insertion may require pre-medication with atropine or consideration of alternative contraceptive methods.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical shock is a vasovagal response that can occur during intrauterine device insertion, characterised by bradycardia and hypotension.","Immediate administration of atropine is the first-line treatment for severe cervical shock.","Patient positioning in Trendelenburg and cessation of the procedure are important supportive measures in cervical shock."],"references":["Sexual Health Victoria. Vasovagal reactions and intrauterine device (IUD) insertions [Internet]. 2023 Feb [cited 2024 Dec 3]. Available from: https://shvic.org.au/assets/resources/SHV_IUD_Vasovagal_Feb23.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52534"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16816"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52534"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T13:26:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T13:27:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9507"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c